{
  "query": "What are the documented benefits and potential negative impacts of releasing captive-bred or head-started toads into the wild?",
  "relevant_summary": "Based on the action documents, the benefits of releasing captive-bred or head-started toads into the wild include population establishment and breeding success. Two of three studies in Denmark, Sweden and the USA found that captive-bred toads released as tadpoles, juveniles or metamorphs established populations, in one case at 70% of sites (Action 875). For amphibians generally, six of 10 studies in Denmark, Spain, the UK and USA found that released head-started tadpoles, metamorphs or juveniles established breeding frog populations or increased populations of frogs or toads, with mixed results showing breeding populations established in 12 of 17 studies reviewed or at two of four sites (Action 881). Nine of 10 studies in Australia, Canada, Europe and the USA found that head-started amphibians released as tadpoles, metamorphs or adults metamorphosed successfully, tended to survive the first season, winter or year or bred successfully (Action 881). One review found that 41% of release programmes of captive-bred or head-started amphibians showed evidence of breeding in the wild for multiple generations, 29% showed some evidence of breeding and 12% evidence of survival following release (Action 871).\n\nHowever, potential negative impacts include population establishment failure and low survival rates. One study found that populations were not established from captive-bred and head-started toads (Action 875). Two studies in Puerto Rico found that survival of released captive-bred Puerto Rican crested toads was low and that 25% were predated within two days of release (Action 875). Two studies found that head-started metamorphs or adults did not prevent a frog population decline or establish a breeding toad population (Action 881). Captive breeding itself may have deleterious effects, with three studies finding evidence for potentially deleterious physiological or genetic changes due to captive breeding, and studies showing reduced genetic diversity in captive populations compared to wild populations (Action 599).",
