{"query": "What are the general outcomes of releasing captive-bred toads, including species like the Mallorcan midwife toad?", "summary": "Studies on releasing captive-bred toads show varied but generally positive outcomes for establishing breeding populations. For Mallorcan midwife toads specifically, three studies found that captive-bred individuals released as tadpoles, toadlets or adults established breeding populations at 38%, 80% or 100% of sites respectively (Action 873). However, one study found that while predator defences were maintained, genetic diversity was reduced in captive-bred reintroduced populations, and toads bred in captivity for nine or more generations showed slower tadpole development, reduction in predator defence traits and decreased genetic diversity (Actions 873, 837).

For other toad species, two of three studies found that captive-bred toads released as tadpoles, juveniles or metamorphs established populations, with success rates of 70% at some sites (Action 875). However, outcomes varied significantly by species - studies of Puerto Rican crested toads found low survival rates with 25% predated within two days of release (Action 875). Head-starting programs showed more positive results, with six of 10 studies finding that released head-started tadpoles, metamorphs or juveniles established breeding populations or increased existing populations (Action 881).

Captive breeding success rates also varied by species and conditions. Ten studies found that various toad species produced eggs successfully in captivity, with eight successfully raising captive-bred toads to tadpoles, toadlets or adults, though two found that most toads died after hatching or metamorphosis (Action 848). For harlequin toads, breeding success was more challenging, with only three of five studies achieving reproduction in captivity (Action 836). Environmental factors significantly affected outcomes, with reproductive success influenced by tank humidity and outdoor enclosures showing higher success rates than indoor tanks (Action 848).", "action_ids": ["873","875","837","848","836","881"]}

