{
  "action_id": "756",
  "action_title": "Install barrier fencing along roads",
  "key_messages": "Key Messages:\n\nSeven of eight studies (including one replicated and two controlled studies) in Germany, Canada and the USA found that barrier fencing with culverts decreased amphibian road deaths, or decreased deaths provided that the fence length and material were effective. One found that low numbers of amphibians were diverted by barriers during breeding migrations.\nOne replicated study in the USA found that barriers at least 0.6 m high were required to prevent green frogs and leopard frogs climbing over. Two studies in the Netherlands and USA found that treefrogs and 10% of common toads climbed over barrier fencing during breeding migrations."
}

tools_called.args:
{"query": "For road mitigation projects, what design factors are associated with the success or failure of tunnels and culverts for amphibian passage?", "summary": "Based on studies of road mitigation projects, several design factors are associated with the success or failure of tunnels and culverts for amphibian passage. Diameter significantly affects usage, with wider culverts used more in three of six studies (Action 884). Length impacts effectiveness, with long culverts avoided in one of two studies (Action 884). Lighting shows mixed effects across all three studies examining this factor (Action 884). Substrate type influences usage, with natural substrates used more than artificial ones in three of six studies (Action 884). The presence of water has mixed effects in two of three studies (Action 884). Entrance location affects usage patterns in one study, and tunnel climate influences usage in one study (Action 884). 

Barrier fencing is crucial for guiding amphibians to entrances, as the majority of effective culverts/tunnels had barrier fencing, and one study found decreased road deaths only when barrier fencing was also installed (Action 884). Barriers must be at least 0.6 m high to prevent green frogs and leopard frogs from climbing over (Action 756). However, some amphibians like treefrogs and 10% of common toads can still climb over barrier fencing during breeding migrations (Action 756).

Certain design features result in failure: one-way tunnels with vertical entry chutes resulted in high mortality of common toads, and condensation deposits from steel culverts had very high metal concentrations (Action 884). Studies of culverts with flowing water show mixed results, with some being used by amphibians and others rarely used or not used at all (Action 884). Despite mitigation efforts, one study found that thousands of amphibians were still killed on roads even with culverts installed (Action 884).", "action_ids": ["884","756"]}

